00:39:40.560 --> 00:39:48.030
What is that ratio
approximately, when k is small?

00:39:48.030 --> 00:39:51.400
What does the sine of
theta look like when

00:39:51.400 --> 00:39:54.280
theta is a small angle?

00:39:54.280 --> 00:39:57.460
Looks like theta, right?

00:39:57.460 --> 00:40:00.200
Sine theta is about theta.

00:40:00.200 --> 00:40:04.070
So this thing is about k delta
x over 2 divided by delta --

00:40:04.070 --> 00:40:15.650
it's k, so it's approximately
k for small delta x, let's say.

00:40:15.650 --> 00:40:18.550
Delta x is small.

00:40:18.550 --> 00:40:23.370
That's the key thing to know
about the sinc function,

00:40:23.370 --> 00:40:27.730
that it begins by approximating
the sine function,

00:40:27.730 --> 00:40:32.390
but then of course, when k delta
x gets large, it wanders away.

00:40:32.390 --> 00:40:33.850
It's not linear in k.

00:40:33.850 --> 00:40:37.620
See, it starts out
practically linear in k,

00:40:37.620 --> 00:40:40.480
and that k is
exactly the right k.

00:40:40.480 --> 00:40:42.220
That's the right factor.

00:40:42.220 --> 00:40:43.400
That's the k here.

00:40:47.680 --> 00:40:49.280
But in the
differential equation,

00:40:49.280 --> 00:40:53.930
it stayed k and in the
difference equation,

00:40:53.930 --> 00:41:02.790
for k delta x moving away,
it changes and that's why --

00:41:02.790 --> 00:41:06.380
of course, that's the
source of the error.

00:41:06.380 --> 00:41:09.790
We're seeing now why
the method is probably

00:41:09.790 --> 00:41:11.720
second-order accuracy.

00:41:11.720 --> 00:41:16.140
We know that these second
differences are second --

00:41:16.140 --> 00:41:18.130
give second-order accuracy.

00:41:18.130 --> 00:41:21.050
This would be -- if I
looked at the next term,

00:41:21.050 --> 00:41:23.650
what's the next
term in sine theta?

00:41:23.650 --> 00:41:26.750
Sine theta starts
out theta and then,

00:41:26.750 --> 00:41:28.440
what's the term after that?

00:41:31.810 --> 00:41:38.480
Everybody's Taylor series or --
[UNINTELLIGIBLE] theta cubed,

00:41:38.480 --> 00:41:40.880
it's a theta cubed term.

00:41:40.880 --> 00:41:45.490
Exactly, it's a minus theta
cubed over 6, three factorial,

00:41:45.490 --> 00:41:47.700
but it's a theta cubed term.

00:41:47.700 --> 00:41:53.110
And so the theta gave
us the right thing

00:41:53.110 --> 00:41:55.580
and then two more
powers of theta

00:41:55.580 --> 00:41:58.070
will give us a
second-order error, right?

00:42:00.880 --> 00:42:08.600
I better move since -- so that's
the story for semidiscrete.

00:42:08.600 --> 00:42:12.620
Semidiscrete produced
a pure exponential,

00:42:12.620 --> 00:42:21.360
but with a phase
factor, you could say,

00:42:21.360 --> 00:42:23.990
that wasn't linear in k
where the real one was.

00:42:26.590 --> 00:42:33.350
Now, what about -- let me
move up to that board above,

00:42:33.350 --> 00:42:38.970
where now we're going to have
-- we have it's discrete in time

00:42:38.970 --> 00:42:43.394
as well, so we're going
to have single steps.

00:42:43.394 --> 00:42:44.810
What's going to
be the difference?

00:42:47.580 --> 00:42:50.530
Again, I'm going
to try -- you know,

00:42:50.530 --> 00:42:56.920
I only have one idea here
-- U_(j, n) will be some G,

00:42:56.920 --> 00:43:04.750
some growth factor, times
e to the i*j*k delta x.

00:43:04.750 --> 00:43:09.740
The same -- I'm going to
try an e to the i*k*x,

00:43:09.740 --> 00:43:14.830
and in the space variable, it
will be G. And after n steps,

00:43:14.830 --> 00:43:17.730
it'll be G n times.

00:43:17.730 --> 00:43:19.910
So this is the discrete, right?

00:43:19.910 --> 00:43:25.400
This is the ansatz,
to use a fancy word.

00:43:25.400 --> 00:43:26.590
This is what you plug in.

00:43:29.550 --> 00:43:31.800
Little crazy to use
the word ansatz, which

00:43:31.800 --> 00:43:36.110
sounds fancy and the word
plug, which is far from fancy.

00:43:36.110 --> 00:43:40.460
I should say substitute.

00:43:40.460 --> 00:43:41.560
Substitute in it.

00:43:41.560 --> 00:43:43.710
All right.

00:43:43.710 --> 00:43:46.990
Do we know what the
process is going to do?

00:43:46.990 --> 00:43:51.900
When I plug it in -- sorry,
substitute it in on the left,

00:43:51.900 --> 00:43:59.710
we get -- and I'm going to
cancel this from every term --

00:43:59.710 --> 00:44:03.090
so all I'm interested
in is the --

00:44:03.090 --> 00:44:05.780
maybe I'll cancel
G to the n minus 1.

00:44:05.780 --> 00:44:08.090
So let me write down what I get.

00:44:08.090 --> 00:44:10.580
This is going to give me
-- in the time direction,

00:44:10.580 --> 00:44:19.080
I'll have a G squared minus a 2G
plus a 1 over delta t squared,

00:44:19.080 --> 00:44:23.650
and in the space direction,
which is at the centered time,

00:44:23.650 --> 00:44:28.330
so it's going to multiply a
G, it's going to be my same,

00:44:28.330 --> 00:44:29.620
my very same thing.

00:44:29.620 --> 00:44:33.260
I could maybe give
it a name here.

00:44:33.260 --> 00:44:35.960
I don't know whether --
should I give it a name?

00:44:35.960 --> 00:44:37.770
I know what it is
anyway, because it's

00:44:37.770 --> 00:44:42.510
the same thing that I had
in the semidiscrete method.

00:44:42.510 --> 00:44:49.130
It's this -- let's see
what it looked like.

00:44:49.130 --> 00:44:57.980
At this point, it was --
look, let's do one thing.

00:44:57.980 --> 00:45:02.010
Let me get this delta t squared
up there times the c squared

00:45:02.010 --> 00:45:03.670
divided by the delta x squared.

00:45:03.670 --> 00:45:08.810
Let me just clean
up those constants,

00:45:08.810 --> 00:45:13.250
so that when I multiply up
by the delta t squared times

00:45:13.250 --> 00:45:18.640
the c squared divided by the
delta x squared, what's that?

00:45:18.640 --> 00:45:24.030
c delta t over delta x squared
is my old ratio, the Courant

00:45:24.030 --> 00:45:31.020
number r, squared, and
then it's this times G.

00:45:31.020 --> 00:45:33.980
So this will all be
just exactly the same

00:45:33.980 --> 00:45:38.380
and that's what I
simplified here.

00:45:38.380 --> 00:45:43.030
Let me just leave it
as -- with a minus.

00:45:43.030 --> 00:45:48.370
Let me remember that I did take
a minus so that I could write

00:45:48.370 --> 00:45:58.400
it as 2 minus 2 cosine of k
delta x times G. Is that --

00:45:58.400 --> 00:46:01.950
I really think I have kept
track of everything here.

00:46:01.950 --> 00:46:07.640
The r squared coming from
all this stuff, the minus 2

00:46:07.640 --> 00:46:11.560
coming here and the plus 2
cosine coming from there.

00:46:11.560 --> 00:46:12.370
You OK with that?

00:46:16.670 --> 00:46:20.510
But there's one new
ingredient here.

00:46:20.510 --> 00:46:27.240
Again, G to the n -- I cancelled
G to the n minus 1 times this

00:46:27.240 --> 00:46:30.340
from every term.

00:46:30.340 --> 00:46:33.850
So the new ingredient, that we
just have five minutes to deal

00:46:33.850 --> 00:46:39.530
with, is the fact
that we have second --

00:46:39.530 --> 00:46:42.760
G squared just showed up.

00:46:42.760 --> 00:46:44.330
So why did G squared show up?

00:46:44.330 --> 00:46:52.000
Because it's a multistep
method and therefore,

00:46:52.000 --> 00:46:53.240
I've got two G's.

00:46:53.240 --> 00:46:54.320
Of course.

00:46:54.320 --> 00:46:57.690
I had two G's in all
these other cases

00:46:57.690 --> 00:46:59.440
because I had second
derivatives and now I

00:46:59.440 --> 00:47:01.160
have second differences.

00:47:01.160 --> 00:47:04.180
So I have two G's, so I
have to solve for G --

00:47:04.180 --> 00:47:07.220
and what is stability
going to depend on?

00:47:07.220 --> 00:47:11.760
Stability is going
to be whether G --

00:47:11.760 --> 00:47:14.090
both G's, because there
are two of them now --

00:47:14.090 --> 00:47:15.750
are less than or equal to 1.

00:47:15.750 --> 00:47:18.510
That's what I have to check
and that's the equation.

00:47:22.490 --> 00:47:24.610
What do we figure?

00:47:24.610 --> 00:47:30.160
We figure that if r is pretty
big -- if r is big, no way.

00:47:30.160 --> 00:47:34.770
If r is big, the
Courant test will fail

00:47:34.770 --> 00:47:37.040
and stability will fail.

00:47:37.040 --> 00:47:40.050
But if r is small,
then I expect --

00:47:40.050 --> 00:47:42.590
I have a right to
hope for stability.

00:47:42.590 --> 00:47:45.500
So it's going to
be the size of r.

00:47:45.500 --> 00:47:48.370
So I just have to -- I've
got this quadratic equation.

00:47:48.370 --> 00:47:50.530
I'm going to bring
this thing over here.

00:47:50.530 --> 00:47:56.520
I'm going to write this as
G squared minus 2a*G plus 1

00:47:56.520 --> 00:48:01.860
equals 0, where a is this
quantity -- So I had minus 2a,

00:48:01.860 --> 00:48:08.240
so a is a 1 from there, and when
I bring this over to the other

00:48:08.240 --> 00:48:13.810
side, it's going to be a plus
r squared -- factoring out --

00:48:13.810 --> 00:48:16.000
notice the 2 is everywhere.

00:48:16.000 --> 00:48:19.190
So I put the 2 here.

00:48:19.190 --> 00:48:23.460
The a comes from the 1
there and from this times

00:48:23.460 --> 00:48:30.670
the r squared 1 plus r squared
minus r squared cos k delta x.

00:48:39.380 --> 00:48:45.560
I'm just doing algebra and
it's coming out nicely.

00:48:45.560 --> 00:48:47.510
It's coming out
to a nice equation

00:48:47.510 --> 00:48:51.080
here with a slightly
messy expression for a,

00:48:51.080 --> 00:48:57.730
but now that I've named this
quantity a, I can solve this.

00:48:57.730 --> 00:48:59.120
So what's the solution?

00:48:59.120 --> 00:49:07.430
I remember the quadratic formula
and I get G as 1, I think,

00:49:07.430 --> 00:49:13.450
plus or minus the square
root of 1 minus a squared.

00:49:16.010 --> 00:49:24.280
That's G. Oh, maybe this
is an a; probably is.

00:49:24.280 --> 00:49:31.450
I guess the quadratic equation
takes a little memorizing,

00:49:31.450 --> 00:49:34.780
but I guess the first point
is that that coefficient shows

00:49:34.780 --> 00:49:38.940
up there and then the
square root that we know.

00:49:41.550 --> 00:49:42.380
So what's up?

00:49:47.440 --> 00:49:50.030
Again, none of this is deep.

00:49:50.030 --> 00:49:56.330
I'm just following
my one-way path.

00:49:56.330 --> 00:49:58.290
Check stability.

00:49:58.290 --> 00:50:02.140
Check the size of G.
Get an equation for G.

00:50:02.140 --> 00:50:06.970
Get a formula for
G and look at it.

00:50:06.970 --> 00:50:12.010
So a is some positive
number and the key

00:50:12.010 --> 00:50:15.790
is going to be whether
a is bigger than 1

00:50:15.790 --> 00:50:17.950
or smaller than 1.

00:50:17.950 --> 00:50:25.160
If a is -- is that right, 1
minus a squared or should that

00:50:25.160 --> 00:50:28.760
be a squared minus 1?

00:50:28.760 --> 00:50:30.150
Is it a squared minus 1?

00:50:32.780 --> 00:50:36.080
Professors are not responsible
for the quadratic formula

00:50:36.080 --> 00:50:41.450
because we proved that we
could do it in third grade

00:50:41.450 --> 00:50:44.110
and lost it since.

00:50:44.110 --> 00:50:46.370
I guess it's right.

00:50:46.370 --> 00:50:49.050
Is that right?

00:50:49.050 --> 00:50:52.150
Because look, here's the story.

00:50:52.150 --> 00:50:55.350
Suppose a is bigger than 1.

00:50:55.350 --> 00:50:59.440
Suppose -- I'm really looking
at the roots of this equation.

00:50:59.440 --> 00:51:01.810
Notice, by the way, the
roots of that equation

00:51:01.810 --> 00:51:04.020
multiply to give 1.

00:51:04.020 --> 00:51:07.240
So I'm on the edge here.

00:51:07.240 --> 00:51:14.220
Either both roots have size 1 or
one of those roots is too big.

00:51:14.220 --> 00:51:17.650
The test is going to be, is
a greater than 1? a greater

00:51:17.650 --> 00:51:28.020
than 1 will be unstable. a
less than 1 will be stable

00:51:28.020 --> 00:51:35.420
and I'll connect a less
than 1 to r less than 1.

00:51:35.420 --> 00:51:39.330
That will give me r less than 1.

00:51:39.330 --> 00:51:39.830
All right.

00:51:39.830 --> 00:51:44.990
I've given away the result
because time is pressing.

00:51:44.990 --> 00:51:49.760
Let me just take the
remaining time to see this.

00:51:49.760 --> 00:51:53.300
Suppose a is bigger than 1.

00:51:53.300 --> 00:51:55.520
I'm just looking at the
roots of this equation

00:51:55.520 --> 00:51:56.820
and here they are.

00:51:56.820 --> 00:52:03.190
If a is bigger than 1, like 2,
I have 2 plus square root of 3,

00:52:03.190 --> 00:52:05.470
I'm way up, right?

00:52:05.470 --> 00:52:07.990
I'm bigger than 1, no question.

00:52:07.990 --> 00:52:11.550
Suppose a is less than 1.

00:52:11.550 --> 00:52:14.420
Suppose a is 1/2.

00:52:14.420 --> 00:52:19.880
Then I have 1/2 plus or minus
the square root of -- what?

00:52:19.880 --> 00:52:21.280
What's up here?

00:52:21.280 --> 00:52:28.440
If a is smaller than 1, this is
negative and if it's negative,

00:52:28.440 --> 00:52:31.800
its square root is imaginary.

00:52:31.800 --> 00:52:33.510
So this is good.

00:52:33.510 --> 00:52:39.200
I have a real part and
then an imaginary part

00:52:39.200 --> 00:52:43.070
and then on some magic
little bit of board,

00:52:43.070 --> 00:52:44.650
I'm going to add their squares.

00:52:44.650 --> 00:52:50.240
So I just want to take the real
parts squared and the imaginary

00:52:50.240 --> 00:52:54.230
part squared -- now the
imaginary part is going to be 1

00:52:54.230 --> 00:53:00.090
minus a squared because
when I bring out an i,

00:53:00.090 --> 00:53:04.310
then I have a 1 minus a squared
there and when I add them,

00:53:04.310 --> 00:53:06.850
I get 1.

00:53:06.850 --> 00:53:09.810
So let me just say
again what it is.

00:53:09.810 --> 00:53:11.880
I just figured out
what is absolute value

00:53:11.880 --> 00:53:16.010
of G squared as
real part squared

00:53:16.010 --> 00:53:19.420
and imaginary part squared
and I got the answer 1.

00:53:19.420 --> 00:53:25.620
So the conclusion is, the roots
are stable when a is below 1

00:53:25.620 --> 00:53:30.120
and I have instability
when a is above 1.

00:53:30.120 --> 00:53:34.620
Then if I track that down,
that reduces to the tests --

00:53:34.620 --> 00:53:37.700
it just happens to be
the same test on r,

00:53:37.700 --> 00:53:41.810
whether r is below 1, which
is the Courant-Friedrichs-Lewy

00:53:41.810 --> 00:53:46.120
condition, that I'm staying
inside the characteristics,

00:53:46.120 --> 00:53:50.920
or r is bigger than 1 and
I'm taking a delta t that

00:53:50.920 --> 00:53:53.540
isn't stable.

00:53:53.540 --> 00:53:56.530
I'm sorry to go
slightly over the time.

00:53:56.530 --> 00:53:58.240
Thanks for staying with me.

00:53:58.240 --> 00:54:03.130
I'll begin next time
with this staggered grid.

00:54:03.130 --> 00:54:05.470
That won't take
the whole lecture,

00:54:05.470 --> 00:54:10.680
but it's worth knowing because
we see staggered grids in many

00:54:10.680 --> 00:54:13.210
of the best methods.

00:54:13.210 --> 00:54:13.760
Thanks.

00:54:13.760 --> 00:54:17.510
Have a good weekend and I guess
it's Tuesday rather than Monday

00:54:17.510 --> 00:54:19.940
that I see you next.

